ngdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Northall, Dunstable, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northall, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Sharpenhoe, Streatley, Central Bedfordshire district, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Streatley, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"nl":{"1478–1553":"1478–1553","1482–Female":"1482–Overleden","1502–1577":"1502–1577","1450–Male":"1450–Overleden","1450–Female":"1450–Overleden","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1478":"1478","1577":"1577","1553":"1553","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Bedford, Bedford district, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northall, Dunstable, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northall, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sharpenhoe, Streatley, Central Bedfordshire district, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Streatley, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1478–1553":"1478–1553","1482–Female":"1482–Deceased","1502–1577":"1502–1577","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1478":"1478","1577":"1577","1553":"1553","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Bedford, Bedford district, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Northall, Dunstable, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northall, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Sharpenhoe, Streatley, Central Bedfordshire district, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Streatley, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Merry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>merie</i>, <i>mirie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ (Old English <i>myrge</i>). Compare   Merriman  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mearadhaigh</b>, <b>Ó Meardha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mearadhach</i>, a descendant of <i>Meardha</i>’, personal names derived from an adjective meaning ‘lively, wild, or high-spirited’. Where Irish <i>dh</i> has been Anglicized as <i>g</i>, there is possible confusion with   Merrick  .","French: variant of   Mery   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Marron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jesus, Armando, Juan, Mario, Carlos, Enrique, Joaquin, Rafael, Alfonso, Alfredo, Alvaro.  Irish Ciaran, Parnell.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mearáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mearán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>mear</i> ‘lively’. Compare   Merry  . There may have been some confusion with   Marrin  .","Spanish (<b>Marrón</b>): nickname from <i>marrón</i> ‘brown’, a word of French origin."]},{"name":"Maree","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mearadhaigh</b> (see   Merry  ).","Dutch (also <b>Marée</b>): problably a topographic name for someone living near marshland, derived from French <i>marais</i> ‘marsh’. Alternatively, from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Marie</i> (see   Maria  , compare 4 below).","Altered form (<b>Marée</b>) of French <b>Maré</b> (see   Mare   4), established in South Africa."]},{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Mery","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Sergio, Alicia, Carolina, Enrique, Felipe, Javier, Jorge, Manuel, Mario, Miguel.  French Michel, Camille.","French: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Médéric</i>, derived from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of <i>mecht</i> ‘strength, might’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power; ruler’.","French: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Aimery</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’."]},{"name":"Merriweather","meanings":["English: nickname for someone of a sunny disposition, from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ (see   Merry  ) + <i>wether</i> ‘weather’. Compare   Fairweather  ."]},{"name":"Marry","meanings":["Irish: from the later pronunciation of <b>Ó Mearadhaigh</b>, see   Merry   2.","English: variant of   Mary  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Merry was born in 1478, in Northall, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Mery, 